{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FUDXqukhENgRQPMBxjRw4j","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: structured-logging-contract\n     3→description: Apply a stable method/step structured logging contract without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Structured Logging Contract (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill for code paths that need stable observability.\n     9→\n    10→## Required Variables\n    11→\n    12→- `target_file`\n    13→- `function_name`\n    14→- `event_namespace`\n    15→- `step_name`\n    16→- `entity_id_expr`\n    17→\n    18→## Execution Checklist\n    19→\n    20→1. Ensure logger setup is present and local to module conventions.\n    21→2. Emit a start event at function entry.\n    22→3. Emit a completion event before return.\n    23→4. Use stable keys: `method`, `step`, `entity_id`.\n    24→5. Keep event names stable as `<event_namespace>.<phase>`.\n    25→\n    26→## Guardrails\n    27→\n    28→- Avoid unstructured free-text-only logs.\n    29→- Avoid PII-heavy payloads in log `extra` data.\n    30→- Keep key names and event names consistent across related methods.\n    31→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57ae1f93-b989-4827-b53d-6756fb79b720","uuid":"61449af3-e4f4-432e-8faa-d0d9267752b6"}
